    <section id="entry-requirements">
        <h2>Entry requirements</h2>

        <ul>
            <li>Each entry must include a unique pairing of script name and applicable langage code. The language code must be a valid [[iso-639-2023]] code. If the text metric guidance is broadly applicable to all languages using that script then "All" should be used. More specific script/language pairings will take precedent over a general script/"All" entry.</li>
            <li>Each entry must include a link that references a publicly available normative specification. It is recommended that such a specification be made available without cost (other than reasonable shipping and handling if not avaiable by online means).</li>
            <li>Specifications external to W3C should follow the principals outlined in the W3C Technical issues Lead Team <a href="https://www.w3.org/guide/process/tilt/normative-references.html">guidance to Normative References</a></li>
            <li>Each referenced specification must include the following sections
                <ul>
                    <li>Blocks of text readable (minimum)</li>
                    <li>Blocks of text readable (enhanced)</li>
                    <li>Text style readable (minimum)</li>
                    <li>Text style readable (enhanced)</li>
                    <li>Blocks of text adjustable</li>
                    <li>Text style adjustable</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Each section must only contain guidance on the specifics of how to present text using the identified script for any specified language.</li>
            <li>Where there are no specific metrics that must be included, a section should still be included with the text "Not applicable".</li>
            <li>Candidate entries must be announced by filing an issue in the <a href="https://www.github.com/w3c/wcag3/issues">WCAG3 GitHub repository</a></li>
            <li>If the Accessibility Guidelines Working Group reaches consensus to accept the candidate, a pull request should be drafted to register the candidate. The registry editors will review and merge the pull request.</li>
            <li>Entries may be updated to include a reference to a more recent version of the referenced specification.</li>
            <li>Entries may be deleted or depricated.</li>
            <li>Deleted or depricated script/language pairings may be reused.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="registry">
        <h2>Registry</h2>

        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Script</th>
                    <th>Language</th>
                    <th>Public specification(s)</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td>Latin</td>
                    <td>All</td>
                    <td>Link to specification outlining Latin based metrics</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </section>
</body>
